  "prompt": "When entering the US will I be detained for a bench warrant?",
  "response": "While I can provide general information, please be aware that legal situations can vary widely based on individual circumstances and location.\n\nA bench warrant is typically issued by a judge when someone fails to appear in court or comply with a court order. If you have a bench warrant, it is possible that you could be detained if the warrant is discovered during your entry into the United States. This can happen if Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) or other relevant authorities run a background check and find the warrant.\n\nThe likelihood of detention may depend on several factors, including:\n\n1. The severity of the offense related to the bench warrant.\n2. Whether the warrant is entered into national databases accessible to immigration authorities.\n3. Existing protocols of the specific port of entry.\n\nIf you suspect you have a bench warrant, it is recommended to address the legal issue before attempting to enter the country. You may wish to consult with a legal professional to better understand your situation and navigate the complexities of the legal system.\n\nRemember, this is general information and does not constitute legal advice.",
